		<title>Who are these PPL?: Five questions, #3</title>
		<link>http://theppl.us/blog/406</link>
		<comments>http://theppl.us/blog/406#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 03 Mar 2012 17:21:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>lila</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Blog]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Five Questions]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theppl.us/?p=406</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Meet Justin Ruckman: PPL co-creator, CLT Blogger and Charlotte native.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>The PPL is diverse, by definition: we are bloggers, photojournalists, artists and entrepreneurs of varied ages and backgrounds committed to supporting independent media during the 2012 DNC. But let’s get a little more specific.</em></p>
<p><em>So who are these PPL, anyway? In this five-question series, you’ll get the quick-and-dirty on the folks making this thing happen.</em></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://theppl.us/406/spacey-big" rel="attachment wp-att-407"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-407" title="spacey-big" src="http://theppl.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/spacey-big-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a>Name?</strong></p>
<p>Justin Ruckman.</p>
<p><strong>Years in Charlotte?</strong></p>
<p>Born and raised, minus some college.</p>
<p><strong>Claim to fame?</strong></p>
<p>Started <a href="http://cltblog.com" target="_blank">CLT Blog</a> four years ago, which now has its own weekly TV show on WTVI</p>
<p><strong>What are you looking forward to at the DNC?</strong></p>
<p>I grew up here, so I love opportunities like this to see our city through the eyes of people who didn&#8217;t. Not to mention I can&#8217;t wait to hang out with all the bloggers &#8212; it&#8217;s gonna be a mini SXSW!</p>
<p><strong>Why are you a part of the PPL?</strong></p>
<p>This project, and online media at large, represent some of my generation&#8217;s most important values: community, transparency, diversity and the application of technology for social good. I want to see more people talking about government, and fewer people talking about politics.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
