		<item>
		<title>Who are these PPL?: Five questions, #2</title>
		<link>http://theppl.us/blog/395</link>
		<comments>http://theppl.us/blog/395#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 02 Mar 2012 19:48:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>lila</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Blog]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Five Questions]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theppl.us/?p=395</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Who is behind the PPL? In today's installment of the Five Questions, meet investigative journalist Rhiannon Fionn-Bowman.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>The PPL is diverse, by definition: we are bloggers, photojournalists, artists and entrepreneurs of varied ages and backgrounds committed to supporting independent media during the 2012 DNC. But let’s get a little more specific.</em></p>
<p><em>So who are these PPL, anyway? In this five-question series, you’ll get the quick-and-dirty on the folks making this thing happen.</em></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://theppl.us/395/rhi" rel="attachment wp-att-396"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-396" title="rhi" src="http://theppl.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/rhi-300x200.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="200" /></a>Name?</strong></p>
<p>Rhiannon Fionn-Bowman</p>
<p><strong>Years in Charlotte?</strong></p>
<p>I’ve lived in Charlotte since 2005. Before that I lived in Atlanta, Ga., and before that Montgomery, Ala.</p>
<p><strong>Claim to fame?</strong></p>
<p>Independent investigative journalist focused on Charlotte’s coal ash issues. I also covered the Jinwright tax evasion trial for <a href="http://Qcitymetro.com" target="_blank">Qcitymetro.com</a> and Occupy Charlotte for <a href="http://clclt.com/" target="_blank">Creative Loafing</a>. I have also written on all of those topics for <em><a href="http://www.charlottemagazine.com/" target="_blank">Charlotte</a></em> magazine.</p>
<p><strong>What are you looking forward to at the DNC?</strong></p>
<p><strong></strong> I’ll be hosting a forum on coal ash for The PPL that will, if all goes as planned, bring in leaders from all sides of the issue and allow time for the community to ask questions. Coal ash is America’s second-largest waste stream and is currently unregulated at the federal level. North Carolina has more high-hazard coal ash ponds than any other state, two of which drain into Charlotte’s main drinking water reservoir.</p>
<p><strong>Why are you a part of the PPL?</strong></p>
<p>Because I believe the people’s voice is just as important as the voices from government and business.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://theppl.us/blog/395/feed</wfw:commentRss>
