		<item>
		<title>Who are these PPL?: Five questions, #1</title>
		<link>http://theppl.us/blog/382</link>
		<comments>http://theppl.us/blog/382#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 02 Mar 2012 03:16:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>lila</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Blog]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Five Questions]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theppl.us/?p=382</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[So who are these PPL, anyway? In this five-question series, you'll get the quick-and-dirty on the folks making this thing happen. Today's feature: Lila Allen.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>The PPL is diverse, by definition: we are bloggers, photojournalists, artists and entrepreneurs of varied ages and backgrounds committed to supporting independent media during the 2012 DNC. But let&#8217;s get a little more specific. </em></p>
<p><em>So who are these PPL, anyway? In this five-question series, you&#8217;ll get the quick-and-dirty on the folks making this thing happen.</em></p>
<p><a href="http://theppl.us/382/brighton" rel="attachment wp-att-383"><img class="size-medium wp-image-383 alignleft" title="brighton" src="http://theppl.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/brighton-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Name?</strong></p>
<p>Lila Allen.</p>
<p><strong>Years in Charlotte?</strong></p>
<p><strong></strong>All 24 so far, though technically I was in Davidson for four. That photo up there obviously isn&#8217;t Charlotte; that&#8217;s Brighton, UK.</p>
<p><strong>Claim to fame?</strong></p>
<p>Most people know me either through my writing (mostly at <a href="http://www.charlotteviewpoint.org" target="_blank">Charlotte Viewpoint</a> or <a href="http://altclt.com" target="_blank">ALT CLT</a>) or through my affiliation with art institutions in town. I&#8217;ve worked at the Mint, McColl Center, the Bechtler, and interned at Center of the Earth Gallery.</p>
<p><strong>What are you looking forward to at the DNC?</strong></p>
<p><strong></strong>I&#8217;m excited to see what local artists and curators are going to come up with for the convention &#8212; I&#8217;m ready for stuff to get weird. Since the whole country will be looking at Charlotte, I think it will give many people the incentive they need to really put themselves out there and get active and creative.</p>
<p><strong>Why are you a part of the PPL?</strong></p>
<p><strong></strong>Having grown up here, Charlotte is important to me. We&#8217;re still learning who we are as a city, and the cool thing about that is that if you want to, you can help shape it. I see the PPL as being a part of that. Getting awesome, talented and diverse people together to support indie media? Count me in. The relationships and momentum we&#8217;re building now until the DNC will continue to serve us well after the out-of-towners have left.</p>
<p>My role at the PPL is to help cover local arts and culture, which is something I find fun anyway. If I can put my thoughts together in a way that helps inform and entertain other people, even better.</p>
<p>(I&#8217;m also the lady posting these nifty interviews. See you tomorrow!)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://theppl.us/blog/382/feed</wfw:commentRss>
